The Familiarity of the New Antisemitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors feel emerging threats to Judaism before they become generally visible?
Because they know that the supposedly "harmless" hints can develop into accusations and eventually lead to discrimination that is then enshrined in law.
At this point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what is at stake.
In this way, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it has become clear that we have every reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other unrefined right-wing extremists in Europe cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" were often foot soldiers of fascism or communism, without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people—connected to the "educated middle class" in conjunction with the mass media, politics, government, and universities—who condemn Israel in a language that often recalls that of the foot soldiers of these antidemocratic movements.
This is not the majority view in the Western world—not yet, fortunately—but it is the voice of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to the United Kingdom should be mentioned: recently, he referred to Israel during a dinner party in London as "this damned little country."
His vulgar language is not particularly alarming.
What is alarming are the reactions to this.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the government call for his recall. In the public sphere, the matter was treated as just another scandal to be filed away.
The French press seriously portrayed the ambassador as a victim of British petty-mindedness rather than his own contemptible attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to the United Kingdom has several allies among Europe's elites.
Ambassador Bernard nevertheless rendered us a service: through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish sentiments are.
As a columnist so aptly formulated: Israel has become a target of hatred, whose name one dares not utter.
We must not only dare to say it, but we are even obligated to speak it out.
Given the daily attacks on Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without having to worry about their safety.
Antisemitic attacks are also reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the fact that the denial of the Holocaust has become commonplace. Nor must we remain silent about the comparisons drawn by antisemites and anti-Zionists between Israel and the Third Reich.
While in a Palestinian television program Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we "must confront the new Nazi plague emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. One hates them almost everywhere."
During the television broadcast of a Friday prayer on Palestinian television, the preacher urged Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. No matter where you are, kill them and these Americans who are just like them."
What we should think about in connection with antisemitism is that it always begins with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If antisemitism is not curbed, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as much as non-Jews.
At the moment, the points of attack in this struggle are blurrier than ever before, because a surprising aspect of today's antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism always remains the same—namely, to attack the Jews—it nevertheless changes its face, its strategy, its justifications, and even its vocabulary.
Once, the Jewish religion was the target.
When these people did not yield, the Jews were expelled or killed.
When in the 19th century racial theory captured people's imagination, Jews were attacked because of their membership in a wicked race.
With the existence of the state of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today slandered as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
Just as with other nations, it is entirely legitimate to critically oppose certain political strategies and decisions of Israel.
Anti-Zionism is becoming increasingly similar to antisemitism.
Anti-Zionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of the United Kingdom, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
One would not believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people, but to hate their state.
And yet there are people associated with Israel who claim to be able to do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, insults against Israel are routine.
This demonization of the only democratic political system in the Middle East is a core element of this new antisemitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of all good and the source of all evil," then within the UN the "doctrine of contempt" circulates, as expressed by Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of Canada's parliament.
This permanent portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is in reality a campaign against the Jewish people.
Thus, the numerous anti-Jewish attacks in many countries are based on demonizations of Israel that employ an antisemitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this defamatory language in connection with the Middle East.
In contrast to earlier anti-Jewish outbursts, today's antisemitism is less about attacks on individual Jews, but rather an attack on the "collective Jew," that is, on the state of Israel.
Such attacks have set off a chain reaction of assaults on individual Jews and Jewish institutions throughout Europe and Latin America.
Earlier, the most dangerous antisemites were those who wanted to make the world Judenrein.
The most dangerous antisemites today are those who want to make the world stateless of Jews.
